{"insight":"Ask the path before comparing roads","publicTitle":"Ask the Path First","plainSummary":"Before comparing two paths, ask whether each one speaks clearly enough within itself.","atAGlance":"A comparison can mislead when one side is already divided. We must see how steady a teaching is among its own followers before weighing it against another. If the inner range is as wide as the outer difference, the result depends on the version chosen.","keyPoints":["Meaning grows clearer when a tradition shows what it can hold steadily.","People can mistake cherry-picking for deep agreement or serious conflict.","Test whether leading versions would change the comparison."],"match":["path agrees with itself"],"tags":["comparison","teaching","care","testing"]}
